<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<handout>
  <title>Worksheet 1.8, An Introduction to Linear Transforms</title>

  <ul marker="">

    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(1) &#160; <em>Written Explanation Exercise</em> </p>
      <p> Suppose <m>T(x) = A x</m> for all <m>x</m> where <m>A</m> is a matrix and <m>T</m> is onto. </p>
      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
          <p>
            What can we say about pivotal rows of <m>A</m>?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            What can we say about the existence of solutions to <m>A x = b</m>?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(2) &#160; Let <m>A</m> be a <m>3 \times 4</m> matrix.  
      What must <m>c</m> and <m>d</m> be if we define the linear transformation
      <m>T : \mathbb{R}^c \to \mathbb{R}^d</m> by <m>T(\vec{x}) = A\vec{x}</m>?</p>
    </li>

    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(3) &#160; Let <m>T : \mathbb{R}^2 \to \mathbb{R}^2</m> be a linear transformation
      such that</p>
      <p>
        <me>
        T\!\left(\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix}\right)
        = x_1 \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
        + x_2 \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>Construct a matrix <m>A</m> so that <m>T(\vec{x}) = A\vec{x}</m> for all vectors <m>\vec{x}</m>.</p>
    </li>

</ul>
<ul marker ="">

    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(4) &#160; Let <m>T : \mathbb{R}^4 \to \mathbb{R}^3</m> be a linear transformation such that</p>
      <p>
        <me>
        T\!\left(
          \begin{bmatrix}
            4 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0
          \end{bmatrix}
        \right)
        =
        T\!\left(
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 4
          \end{bmatrix}
        \right)
        \neq \vec{0}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>Identify a non‑trivial solution <m>\vec{x}</m> to <m>T(\vec{x}) = \vec{0}</m>.</p>
    </li>

    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(5) &#160; Let <m>T_A</m> be the linear transformation with matrix <m>A</m> below.
      Match each choice of <m>A</m> on the left with the geometric description of <m>T_A</m> on the right.</p>

      <table>
        <title>Match the matrices on the left to their descriptions on the right! </title>
        <tabular halign="center">
            <row>
            <cell><m>
                \begin{pmatrix} 0.5 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 0.5 \end{pmatrix}
                </m> </cell>
            <cell>rotation by <m>90^\circ</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
            <cell><m>
                \begin{pmatrix} 0 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1 \end{pmatrix}
                </m></cell>
            <cell>A shear</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
            <cell><m>
                \begin{pmatrix} 0 &amp; -1 \\ 1 &amp; 0 \end{pmatrix}
                </m></cell>
            <cell>projection onto the <m>y</m>-axis</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
            <cell><m>
                \begin{pmatrix} 1 &amp; 1 \\ 0 &amp; 1 \end{pmatrix}
                </m></cell>
            <cell>dilation by <m>\tfrac{1}{2}</m></cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
     </table>
    </li>

  </ul>
</handout>